 a well-educated man, Mr. Cooper. A scientist? Engineer.<br>C: COOPER PRINCIPAL<br>D: Frankly, the world doesn\'t need any more engineers. We didn\'t run out of trains or television sets or satellites. We ran out of food.<br>E: beat<br>C: PRINCIPAL<br>D: The world needs farmers, Mr. Cooper. And I\'m sure your son Tom is going to make a fine one. We\'re a caretaker generation. But things are getting better. Maybe your grandchildren will be able to attend college. Cooper looks down, swallowing his anger. Are we done?<br>E: CONT\'D smiles benignly<br>C: COOPER PRINCIPAL<br>D: One more thing. Ms. Kelly here says that Murph brought a book to school about the lunar landings. He slides an old textbook with a picture of a rocket on the cover across the desk to Cooper.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: One of my old textbooks. the pictures.<br>N: Murph liked<br>C: MS. KELLY<br>D: This is one of the old federal textbooks. We\'ve replaced them with corrected versions. Corrected?<br>C: COOPER MS. KELLY<br>D: The new textbooks explain that the Apollo lunar missions were faked in order to bankrupt the Soviet Union.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: You don\'t believe we went to the moon?<br>C: MS. KELLY<br>D: I believe it was a brilliant piece of propaganda. The Soviets spent years trying to build rockets and other useless machines.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: Useless machines\"?<br>C: MS. KELLY<br>D: Yes, Mr. Cooper. The kind of wastefulness and excess that the 20th century represented. Your children would be better off learning about this planet, rather than reading fantasies about leaving it. Cooper is silent for a long moment.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: One of those useless machines they used to make was called an MRI. If we had any of them left the doctors might have been able to find the cyst in my wife\'s brain before she died, rather than afterwards. And then my kids could have been raised by two parents, instead of me and their pain-in-the-ass grandfather. Ms. Kelly\'s face falls, ashen. Most of it, anyway.<br>N: Cooper swallows his anger.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: You ever consider the best thing for the world and humanity might have been for us to part company? Cooper gets up to leave. INT. TRUCK, COUNTY SCHOOL PARKING LOT -- DAY Cooper climbs into the truck, trying to hold it together.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: He PUNCHES the wheel.<br>D: The radio KEYS to life. He ignores it. Sits for a moment in misery. Finally he picks up the handset.<br>C: CB OPERATOR<br>D: Got a call from Riggs, down in Galveston. Says some of the tractors you built him went haywire last night.<br>E: O.S.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: Just tell him to power down the controllers for a couple minutes.<br>C: CB OPERATOR<br>D: I did. He wants you to come down in person anyway. Says he found something you should take a look at.<br>E: O.S.<br><br></p>\"\"','\"INT. TRUCK\"','\"DAY\"'),(0,'0_120','\"<p id=120>Scene 120: EXT. AIRLOCK, SPACE STATION<br>N: Brand follows Cooper as he walks up to the Endurance.<br>C: BRAND<br>D: You know it doesn\'t work. isn\'t possible.<br>N: Time travel<br>C: COOPER<br>D: You don\'t know that.<br>C: BRAND<br>D: Yes, I do. If it worked, the Chinese would have suddenly discovered all of these incredible technologies. But they never made it. You can\'t go back, Cooper. You can slow things down, but you can\'t ever go back. Our home is gone. You listened to all of those messages from your family. If you had made it back, we would already know. There would already be some evidence. Cooper looks at the machine.<br>E: beat off his look<br>C: BRAND<br>D: If you try to use it, you\'ll die, just like the people who built it. She puts an arm on his shoulder.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: BRAND<br>D: Roth was right, Cooper. We have to keep going. Keep exploring. We have an obligation to try to survive. From here we could find a thousand places where life could thrive. And you\'re going to return to the one place where it can\'t.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: COOPER I made a promise.<br>D: He turns away from her, resolute. EXT. HANGAR,