clustered at the base of the rocket. A smaller, human sized robot is staring at the rocket, giving them instructions. The robot looks up. This is CASE, the leader of the mission. Originally an air force pararescue officer, every part of him, from his alloy chassis to his voice, was designed to inspire respect and confidence. He turns to Cooper.<br>E: laughs off her look<br>C: CASE<br>D: You\'re the man who brought us the probe? Thank you. We tested the telemetry board you warned us about. It failed under high voltage, just as you said. Come with me, please. Case strides off. INT.<br>E: off his look<br>N: MISSION CONTROL, UNDERGROUND HANGAR -- DAY The lights dim as Brand\'s father brings up a schematic of our solar system. Case points to the picture of the ice planet recovered from the probe.<br>C: CASE<br>D: You\'re right, Mr. Cooper. The planet you saw is a long way from earth. A very long way indeed. Brand looks down.<br>N: Case notices.<br>C: CASE<br>D: Our science officer doesn\'t think I should trust you with any of this. One of the curious things about humans is that the more alike you are, the more initially hostile you are to each other. As if by design. Brand makes eye contact with Cooper, then looks away, embarrassed.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: CASE<br>D: I\'ve found the best way to earn a person\'s trust is to trust them.<br>E: CONT\'D MORE<br>C: CASE<br>D: Go ahead, John. Brand\'s father taps a few keys and the schematic he built fifty years beforehand flickers onto the screen.<br>E: CONT\'D looks at Brand\'s father<br>C: BRAND\'S FATHER<br>D: It\'s a wormhole. A shortcut leading to a galaxy on the far side of the universe. We found it fifty years ago. Cooper looks at the animatic, taking it in.<br>C: BRAND\'S FATHER<br>D: We\'ve been waiting, sending probes into it for decades. None of them ever came back. Not until now. Case walks to the schematic.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>N: Looks at it.<br>C: CASE<br>D: Based on the information on the probe, we\'re finally preparing to send the manned mission.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: That rocket doesn\'t have enough thrust or fuel to get you to Jupiter.<br>C: CASE<br>D: The main ship was built in orbit. It has nuclear engines, with enough fuel to last for several years. Cooper looks at the schematic.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: Why are you telling me this? I already told you I\'m not going to tell anyone about this place.<br>C: CASE<br>D: I know you won\'t, Mr. Cooper. We\'re telling you this because I want you to join us. Cooper looks at him.<br>N: Is he serious?<br>C: CASE<br>D: The probe has taken a great deal longer to return to us than we hoped.<br>E: CONT\'D MORE<br>C: CASE<br>D: Dr. Brand\'s Father and several other members of our crew have gotten... older. Brand\'s Father looks down, stoic.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>N: Brand looks angry.<br>C: CASE<br>D: We need someone who can run the systems, improvise, work with what\'s available. All of the skills you seem to have developed.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: COOPER<br>D: But I don\'t have any of the experience. Any training. You people have been preparing for this for years. Case shakes his head.<br>C: CASE<br>D: Humans worry about things like rank and experience. I\'m only concerned with whether someone would be useful. I think you\'d be useful, Mr. Cooper. Cooper is stunned. This is the offer he\'s waited his whole life for. And it\'s come too late. No.<br>E: beat<br>C: COOPER<br>D: I\'m sorry.<br>N: Cooper is deeply conflicted. behind. But he can\'t leave his boys<br>C: COOPER<br>D: I can\'t help you. I have responsibilities. Things that, no offense, are more important than a scientific mission. Case shakes his head.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: CASE<br>D: I\'m not a scientist, Mr. Cooper. And this is not a scientific mission. It\'s a rescue mission. He rises and shakes Cooper\'s hand.<br>C: CASE<br>D: Brand can show you the way out. hope you\'ll reconsider.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>N: I 38.* Case steps to the door. Rescue? Cooper looks at Brand.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: Rescue who? CUT