lanet with oxygen. Water.<br>E: quiet<br>C: BRAND<br>D: A new home for humanity. We\'ll set up a colony, then return to bring more people across.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: But you\'d still only be able to save a few hundred. Maybe a thousand.<br>C: BRAND<br>D: Would it be better if we all died? She looks him directly in the eye.<br>C: BRAND<br>D: Look -- I don\'t have a clue what Case thinks you could add to the mission. You can come with us or you can stay here and wait to die.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: I don\'t care.<br>D: But make no mistake -- this mission is our last chance.<br>E: beat<br><br></p>\"','\"INT.\"','\"NULL\"'),(0,'0_36','\"<p id=36>Scene 36: EXT. FIELD, SANTA CRUZ ISLAND -- NIGHT<br>N: Cooper walks Murph back to the plane. He looks back at Brand, who holds his eye for a beat, then turns back into the light of the underground facility. Cooper buckles Murph into his seat.<br>T: CUT TO:<br><br></p>\"','\"EXT. FIELD, SANTA CRUZ ISLAND\"','\"NIGHT\"'),(0,'0_37','\"<p id=37>Scene 37: EXT. AIRFIELD -- NIGHT<br>N: Cooper\'s airplane touches down heavily on the runway.<br><br></p>\"','\"EXT. AIRFIELD\"','\"NIGHT\"'),(0,'0_38','\"<p id=38>Scene 38: EXT. FARMHOUSE -- NIGHT<br>N: Cooper carries his sleeping son into the house.<br><br></p>\"','\"EXT. FARMHOUSE\"','\"NIGHT\"'),(0,'0_39','\"<p id=39>Scene 39: INT. FARMHOUSE -- NIGHT<br>N: Donald is sitting at the kitchen table, lost in thought. Cooper has told him everything.<br>C: DONALD<br>D: You get older, sometimes you just want to sit back and watch it all play out. Your life. Your kids\' lives. The whole crazy story. I didn\'t think I\'d be around for the end of it. He looks at Cooper.<br>E: looks down<br>C: DONALD<br>D: You have to go.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: I can\'t go.<br>D: the boys.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: I have to look after<br>C: DONALD<br>D: You\'ve been preparing these boys to be on their own since their mom died. Besides, I\'ll be here to look after them, same as I\'ve always been.<br>C: COOPER<br>D: I have a responsibility to them-DONALD That\'s right. You do.<br>T: CUT TO:<br><br></p>\"','\"INT. FARMHOUSE\"','\"NIGHT\"'),(0,'0_4','\"<p id=4>Scene 4: INT. MAIN CONFERENCE ROOM, LIGO, CALTECH -- DAY<br>N: Ansen sits, alone, on one side of a conference table. The other side is filled with GOVERNMENT MEN -- NSA mostly, some DIA. The door opens and his assistant steps in. Armed guards pat him down, then shove him into a seat.<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: Is that really necessary? One of the NSA agents leans forward.<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: You\'ve been complaining for years that the government doesn\'t take your project seriously enough, Doctor. You can\'t have it both ways. Ansen motions to his assistant, who turns on a projector. On-screen, we see the familiar pulse and echoes.<br>E: smiles<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: Yesterday morning, our facility in Hanford identified this signal: a neutron star colliding with a supermassive black hole. We went through the last year\'s data and triangulated the source. The pulse is translated into a crude animatic of a neutron star circling into the black hole.<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: We know that, Doctor. What we don\'t know is why, according to your numbers, this event took place right here in our own solar system. Suddenly, the image overlays the sun, the earth, and the rest of our solar system around the black hole.<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: It didn\'t. Because if it had we\'d all be dead by now. On-screen, Jupiter, then the Earth and the inner planets are consumed by the black hole. Only the sun survives, pulled into orbit around its new master.<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: Which leaves only one explanation: The signal traveled through a<br>E: CONT\'D MORE<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: wormhole. A gateway to a distant corner of the universe. The black hole is on the far side. On-screen, the black hole system is removed to a distant corner, connected to ours by a tunnel through space-time. A gravity wave from the collision travels through the tunnel.<br>E: CONT\'D<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: I\'ve read your book, Doctor. You said that wormholes are impossible.<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: There is nothing quite as satisfying as being proved utterly wrong. I said that a wormhole couldn\'t exist naturally. Not for more than a few billionths of a second. It would have to be... stabilized.<br>E: smiles<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: Stabilized by what? Ansen pauses, unsure.<br>N: His assistant steps in to his defense.<br>C: ASSISTANT<br>D: We don\'t have any way to answer that question.<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: You\'re not under peer review here, Doctor. I don\'t care about your reputation. I need to know how that thing got there. Now. Ansen finally speaks up.<br>E: ignores him<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: If you\'re worried about an invasion, I would start drafting the articles of surrender. Whoever they are, if they can build a wormhole, they could erase us in the blink of an eye. Luckily, that also means we have nothing they could be interested in.<br>E: smiles<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: Then why is it there?<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: I don\'t know. Maybe it\'s an invitation. A chance to commune with an advanced species. The assistant, embarrassed, looks down.<br>N: The agent notices.<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: You don\'t agree?<br>C: ASSISTANT<br>D: No. I don\'t think we can assume an alien intelligence built the wormhole. But the opportunity it represents is incredible. We could explore parts of the universe we never dreamt of reaching in our lifetimes. The agent exchanges a look with one of his colleagues, who steps out of the room.<br>E: delicate changes tack<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: We need to get back to work. I have a conference call with our European partners in fifteen minutes.<br>C: NSA AGENT<br>D: We severed the connections to your European partners this morning.<br>C: ANSEN<br>D: You can\'t do that. The Europeans put up some of the funding...<br>E: indignant<br>C: GOVERNMENT MAN<br>D: We\'ll send them a check. Your project is now classified under the State Secrets Act. He steps out the door, leaving the men 